05041nam a22009975i 9780228012467DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280124677 a10.1515/97802280124672doi  a(DE-B1597)657466  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX8525.8.R9bB29 2022 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a289.9/20947792231 aBaran, Emily B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTo Make a Village Soviet :bJehovah's Witnesses and the Transformation of a Postwar Ukrainian Borderland /cEmily B. Baran. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCast of Characters -- tIntroduction -- tThe Village -- tThe Passport -- tThe Draft -- tThe Ballot Box -- tThe State Bonds -- tThe School -- tThe Farm -- tThe Trial -- tRelease -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn June 1949 the Soviet state arrested seven farmers from the village of Bila Tserkva. Not wealthy or powerful, the men were unknown outside their community, and few had ever heard of their small, isolated village on the southwestern border of Soviet Ukraine. Nevertheless, the state decided they were dangerous traitors who threatened to undermine public order, and a regional court sentenced them to twenty-five years of imprisonment for treason.In To Make a Village Soviet Emily Baran explores why a powerful state singled out these individuals for removal from society. Bila Tserkva had to become a space in which Soviet laws and institutions reigned supreme, yet Sovietization was an aspiration as much it was a reality. The arrested men belonged to a small and misunderstood religious minority, the Jehovah’s Witnesses, and both Witnesses and their neighbours challenged the government’s attempts to fully integrate the village into socialist society. Drawing from the case file and interviews with the families of survivors, Baran argues that what happened in Bila Tserkva demonstrates the sheer ambition of the state’s plans for the Sovietization of borderland communities.A compelling history, To Make a Village Soviet looks to Bila Tserkva to explore the power and the limits of state control – and the possibilities created by communities that resist assimilation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGovernment, Resistance tozUkrainezBila T︠S︡erkva (Zakarpats'ka oblast')xHistoryy20th century. 0aJehovah's WitnessesxPersecutionszUkrainezBila T︠S︡erkva (Zakarpats'ka oblast')xHistoryy20th century. 0aJehovah's WitnesseszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aJehovah's WitnesseszUkrainezBila T︠S︡erkva (Zakarpats'ka oblast')xHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aArmageddon.  aArticle 58.  aBible Students.  aGulag.  aJehovahs Witnesses.  aKGB.  aProtestant.  aRomanian.  aRussia.  aSoviet Union.  aSovietization.  aStalin.  aSubcarpathia.  aTisa River.  aTranscarpathia.  aUSSR.  aUkraine.  aWW2.  aWatchtower.  aWorld War II.  aZakarpattia.  aZakatpate.  aarchives.  aborderlands.  acollectivization.  acommunism.  aevangelism.  afreedom.  ainvestigation.  apersecution.  apropaganda.  aproselytism.  areligion.  arepression.  arural.  ascapegoats.  asects.  asecularization.  asecurity.  asocialism.  asurveillance.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801246740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228012467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780